{
  "doc_id": "16171",
  "text": "The mitochondrial components involved in damage and protection are several, including those seen above. Specifically in cardiac protection, we may have the mitochondrial translocation of some elements of RISK pathway and/or STAT3 of SAFE pathway [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . These enzymes will induce phosphorylation of several components of mitochondria including the putative elements of mPTP and mK ATP channels which will preserve mitochondrial integrity and will mediate protection. On the contrary, in non-protected hearts, there is the intervention of death factors, such as PKCd and Beclin-1, which may modify mitochondria function inducing all forms of cell death [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . In addition, in the reperfusion phase, the abrupt recovery of pH, Ca 2? overload and the overwhelming presence of ROS may be responsible for mPTP formation and RIRR, which may induce redox stress. Interestingly, a lower threshold for triggering the mPTP opening in response to Ca 2? overload and an increased ROS generation has been associated with the higher susceptibility of late pregnant rodent hearts to I/R injury [CITATION_7] .",
